# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cloud-edge-computing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] A **content delivery network** (**CDN**) or **content distribution network** is a geographically distributed network of proxy servers and corresponding data centers.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] CDNs provide high availability and performance ("speed") through geographical distribution relative to end users, and arose in the late 1990s to alleviate the performance bottlenecks of the Internet as it was becoming a critical medium.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Since then, CDNs have grown to serve a large portion of Internet content, including text, graphics and scripts, downloadable objects (media files, software, and documents), applications (e-commerce, portals), live streaming media, on-demand streaming media, and social media services.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] CDNs are a layer in the internet ecosystem.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Content owners such as media companies and e-commerce vendors pay CDN operators to deliver their content to their end users.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] In turn, a CDN pays Internet service providers (ISPs), carriers, and network operators for hosting its servers in their data centers.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] CDN vendors may cross over into other industries like security, DDoS protection and web application firewalls (WAF), and WAN optimization.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Content delivery service providers include Akamai Technologies, Cloudflare, Amazon CloudFront, Qwilt (Cisco), Fastly, CDN77, BunnyCDN, EdgeNext, and Google Cloud CDN.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] CDN nodes are usually deployed in multiple locations, often over multiple Internet backbones.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Benefits include reducing bandwidth costs, improving page load times, and increasing the global availability of content.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] The number of nodes and servers making up a CDN varies, depending on the architecture, some reaching thousands of nodes with tens of thousands of servers on many remote points of presence (PoPs).
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Others build a global network and have a small number of geographical PoPs.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Requests for content are typically algorithmically directed to nodes that are optimal in some way.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for performance, locations that are best for serving content to the user may be chosen.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] This may be measured by choosing locations that are the fewest hops or the shortest time to the requesting client, or the highest server performance, to optimize delivery across local networks.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for cost, locations that are the least expensive may be chosen instead.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] In an optimal scenario, these two goals tend to align, as **edge servers** that are close to the end user at the edge of the network may have an advantage in performance and cost.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Most CDN providers will provide their services over a varying, defined, set of PoPs, depending on the coverage desired, such as United States, Asia-Pacific, International or Global, etc.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] These sets of PoPs can be called "edges", "edge nodes", "edge servers", or "edge networks" as they would be the closest edge of CDN assets to the end user.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] CDN providers profit either from direct fees paid by content providers using their network, or profit from the user analytics and tracking data collected as their scripts are being loaded onto customers' websites inside their browser origin.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] As such these services are being pointed out as potential privacy intrusions for the purpose of behavioral targeting and solutions are being created to restore single-origin serving and caching of resources.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] In particular, a website using a CDN may violate the EU's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] For example, in 2021 a German court forbade the use of a CDN on a university website, because this caused the transmission of the user's IP address to the CDN, which violated the GDPR.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] CDNs serving JavaScript have also been targeted as a way to inject malicious content into pages using them.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Subresource Integrity mechanism was created in response to ensure that the page loads a script whose content is known and constrained to a hash referenced by the website author.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] The Internet was designed according to the end-to-end principle.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] This principle keeps the core network relatively simple and moves the intelligence as much as possible to the network end-points: the hosts and clients.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] As a result, the core network is specialized, optimized, and simplified to only forward data packets.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Content Delivery Networks extend the transport network by distributing on it a variety of intelligent applications employing techniques designed to optimize content delivery.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] The resulting tightly integrated overlay uses web caching, server-load balancing, request routing, and content services.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Web caches store popular content on servers that have the greatest demand for the content requested.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] These shared network appliances reduce bandwidth requirements, reduce server load, and improve the client response times for content stored in the cache.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Web caches are populated based on requests from users (pull caching) or based on preloaded content disseminated from content servers (push caching).
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Server-load balancing uses one or more techniques including service-based (global load balancing) or hardware-based (i.e. layer 4–7 switches, also known as a web switch, content switch, or multilayer switch) to share traffic among a number of servers or web caches.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Here the switch is assigned a single virtual IP address.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Traffic arriving at the switch is then directed to one of the real web servers attached to the switch.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] This has the advantage of balancing load, increasing total capacity, improving scalability, and providing increased reliability by redistributing the load of a failed web server and providing server health checks.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] A content cluster or service node can be formed using a layer 4–7 switch to balance load across a number of servers or a number of web caches within the network.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Request routing directs client requests to the content source best able to serve the request.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] This may involve directing a client request to the service node that is closest to the client, or to the one with the most capacity.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] A variety of algorithms are used to route the request.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] These include Global Server Load Balancing, DNS-based request routing, Dynamic metafile generation, HTML rewriting, and anycasting.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Proximity—choosing the closest service node—is estimated using a variety of techniques including reactive probing, proactive probing, and connection monitoring.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] CDNs use a variety of methods of content delivery including, but not limited to, manual asset copying, active web caches, and global hardware load balancers.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Several protocol suites are designed to provide access to a wide variety of content services distributed throughout a content network.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] The Internet Content Adaptation Protocol (ICAP) was developed in the late 1990s to provide an open standard for connecting application servers.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] A more recently defined and robust solution is provided by the Open Pluggable Edge Services (OPES) protocol.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] This architecture defines OPES service applications that can reside on the OPES processor itself or be executed remotely on a Callout Server.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Edge Side Includes or ESI is a small markup language for edge-level dynamic web content assembly.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] It is fairly common for websites to have generated content.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] It could be because of changing content like catalogs or forums, or because of the personalization.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] This creates a problem for caching systems.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] To overcome this problem, a group of companies created ESI.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] In *peer-to-peer (P2P)* content-delivery networks, clients provide resources as well as use them.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] This means that, unlike client–server systems, the content-centric networks can actually perform better as more users begin to access the content (especially with protocols such as Bittorrent that require users to share).
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] This property is one of the major advantages of using P2P networks because it makes the setup and running costs very small for the original content distributor.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] To incentive peers to participate in the P2P network, web3 and blockchain technologies can be used: participating nodes receive crypto tokens in exchange of their involvement.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] If content owners are not satisfied with the options or costs of a commercial CDN service, they can create their own CDN.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] A private CDN consists of PoPs (points of presence) that are only serving content for their owner.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] These PoPs can be caching servers, reverse proxies or application delivery controllers.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] It can be as simple as two caching servers, or large enough to serve petabytes of content.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] When a private CDN is deployed within a company network, it is also referred as Entreprise CDN or **eCDN**.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Large content distribution networks may even build and set up their own private network to distribute copies of content across cache locations.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Such private networks are usually used in conjunction with public networks as a backup option in case the capacity of the private network is not enough or there is a failure which leads to capacity reduction.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Since the same content has to be distributed across many locations, a variety of multicasting techniques may be used to reduce bandwidth consumption.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Over private networks, it has also been proposed to select multicast trees according to network load conditions to more efficiently utilize available network capacity.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] The rapid growth of streaming video traffic required large capital expenditures by broadband providers in order to meet this demand and retain subscribers by delivering a sufficiently good quality of experience.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] To address this, telecommunications service providers have begun to launch their own content delivery networks as a means to lessen the demands on the network backbone and reduce infrastructure investments.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Because they own the networks over which video content is transmitted, telco CDNs have advantages over traditional CDNs.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] They own the last mile and can deliver content closer to the end-user because it can be cached deep in their networks.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] This deep caching minimizes the distance that video data travels over the general Internet and delivers it more quickly and reliably.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Telco CDNs also have a built-in cost advantage since traditional CDNs must lease bandwidth from them and build the operator's margin into their own cost model.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] In addition, by operating their own content delivery infrastructure, telco operators have better control over the utilization of their resources.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Content management operations performed by CDNs are usually applied without (or with very limited) information about the network (e.g., topology, utilization etc.) of the telco-operators with which they interact or have business relationships.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] These pose a number of challenges for the telco-operators who have a limited sphere of action in face of the impact of these operations on the utilization of their resources.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] In contrast, the deployment of telco-CDNs allows operators to implement their own content management operations, which enables them to have a better control over the utilization of their resources and, as such, provide better quality of service and experience to their end users.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] In June 2011, StreamingMedia.com reported that a group of TSPs had founded an Operator Carrier Exchange (OCX) to interconnect their networks and compete more directly against large traditional CDNs like Akamai and Limelight Networks, which have extensive PoPs worldwide.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] This way, telcos are building a Federated CDN offering, which is more interesting for a content provider willing to deliver its content to the aggregated audience of this federation.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] It is likely that in a near future, other telco CDN federations will be created.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] They will grow by enrollment of new telcos joining the federation and bringing network presence and their Internet subscriber bases to the existing ones.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] The Open Caching specification by Streaming Video Technology Alliance defines a set of APIs that allows a Content Provider to deliver its content using several CDNs in a consistent way, seeing each CDN provider the same way through these APIs.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Combining several CDN services allow Content Providers to not rely on a single CDN service, especially concerned to deal with high peak audience during live events.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] There are several ways to allocate traffic to a particular CDN among the list, either client-side CDN selection, or server-side (at the Content Provider's origin) or cloud-side (in the middle, between the content origin and the audience).
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] CDN selection criteria can be performance, availability and cost.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Traditionally, CDNs have used the IP of the client's recursive DNS resolver to geo-locate the client.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] While this is a sound approach in many situations, this leads to poor client performance if the client uses a non-local recursive DNS resolver that is far away.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] For instance, a CDN may route requests from a client in India to its edge server in Singapore, if that client uses a public DNS resolver in Singapore, causing poor performance for that client.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Indeed, a recent study showed that in many countries where public DNS resolvers are in popular use, the median distance between the clients and their recursive DNS resolvers can be as high as a thousand miles.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] In August 2011, a global consortium of leading Internet service providers led by Google announced their official implementation of the edns-client-subnet IETF Internet Draft, which is intended to accurately localize DNS resolution responses.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] The initiative involves a limited number of leading DNS service providers, such as Google Public DNS, and CDN service providers as well.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] With the edns-client-subnet EDNS0 option, CDNs can now utilize the IP address of the requesting client's subnet when resolving DNS requests.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] This approach, called end-user mapping, has been adopted by CDNs and it has been shown to drastically reduce the round-trip latencies and improve performance for clients who use public DNS or other non-local resolvers.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] However, the use of EDNS0 also has drawbacks as it decreases the effectiveness of caching resolutions at the recursive resolvers, increases the total DNS resolution traffic, and raises a privacy concern of exposing the client's subnet.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Virtualization technologies are being used to deploy virtual CDNs (vCDNs) (also known as a software-defined CDN or sd-CDN) with the goal to reduce content provider costs, and at the same time, increase elasticity and decrease service delay.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] With vCDNs, it is possible to avoid traditional CDN limitations, such as performance, reliability and availability since virtual caches are deployed dynamically (as virtual machines or containers) in physical servers distributed across the provider's geographical coverage.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] As the virtual cache placement is based on both the content type and server or end-user geographic location, the vCDNs have a significant impact on service delivery and network congestion.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] To boost performance, delivery to clients from servers can use alternate non-HTTP protocols such as WebRTC and WebSockets.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] In 2017, Addy Osmani of Google started referring to software solutions that could integrate naturally with the Responsive Web Design paradigm (with particular reference to the <picture> element) as **Image CDN**s.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] The expression referred to the ability of a web architecture to serve multiple versions of the same image through HTTP, depending on the properties of the browser requesting it, as determined by either the browser or the server-side logic.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] The purpose of Image CDNs was, in Google's vision, to serve high-quality images (or, better, images perceived as high-quality by the human eye) while preserving download speed, thus contributing to a great User experience (UX).
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Arguably, the *Image CDN* term was originally a misnomer, as neither Cloudinary nor Imgix (the examples quoted by Google in the 2017 guide by Addy Osmani) were, at the time, a CDN in the classical sense of the term.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Shortly afterwards, though, several companies offered solutions that allowed developers to serve different versions of their graphical assets according to several strategies.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] Many of these solutions were built on top of traditional CDNs, such as Akamai, CloudFront, Fastly, Edgecast and Cloudflare.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/content-delivery-network] At the same time, other solutions that already provided an image multi-serving service joined the Image CDN definition by either offering CDN functionality natively (ImageEngine) or integrating with one of the existing CDNs (Cloudinary/Akamai, Imgix/Fastly).
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] The term began being used in the 1990s to describe content delivery networks—these were used to deliver website and video content from servers located near users.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] In the early 2000s, these systems expanded their scope to hosting other applications, leading to early edge computing services.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] These services could do things like find dealers, manage shopping carts, gather real-time data, and place ads.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] The Internet of things (IoT), where devices are connected to the Internet, is often linked with edge computing.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Edge computing involves running computer programs that deliver quick responses close to where requests are made.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Karim Arabi, during an IEEE DAC 2014 keynote and later at an MIT MTL Seminar in 2015, described edge computing as computing that occurs outside the cloud, at the network's edge, particularly for applications needing immediate data processing.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Edge computing is often equated with fog computing, particularly in smaller setups.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] However, in larger deployments, such as smart cities, fog computing serves as a distinct layer between edge computing and cloud computing, with each layer having its own responsibilities.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] "The State of the Edge" report explains that edge computing focuses on servers located close to the end-users.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Alex Reznik, Chair of the ETSI MEC ISG standards committee, defines 'edge' loosely as anything that's not a traditional data center.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] In cloud gaming, edge nodes, known as "gamelets", are typically within one or two network hops from the client, ensuring quick response times for real-time games.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Edge computing might use virtualization technology to simplify deploying and managing various applications on edge servers.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] In 2018, the world's data was expected to grow 61 percent to 175 zettabytes by 2025.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] According to research firm Gartner, around 10 percent of enterprise-generated data is created and processed outside a traditional centralized data center or cloud.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] By 2025, the firm predicts that this figure will reach 75 percent.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] The increase in IoT devices at the edge of the network is producing a massive amount of data — storing and using all that data in cloud data centers pushes network bandwidth requirements to the limit.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Despite the improvements in network technology, data centers cannot guarantee acceptable transfer rates and response times, which often is a critical requirement for many applications.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Furthermore, devices at the edge constantly consume data coming from the cloud, forcing companies to decentralize data storage and service provisioning, leveraging physical proximity to the end user.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] In a similar way, the aim of edge computing is to move the computation away from data centers towards the edge of the network, exploiting smart objects, mobile phones, or network gateways to perform tasks and provide services on behalf of the cloud.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] By moving services to the edge, it is possible to provide content caching, service delivery, persistent data storage, and IoT management resulting in better response times and transfer rates.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] At the same time, distributing the logic to different network nodes introduces new issues and challenges.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] The distributed nature of this paradigm introduces a shift in security schemes used in cloud computing.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] In edge computing, data may travel between different distributed nodes connected via the internet, and thus requires special encryption mechanisms independent of the cloud.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] This approach minimizes latency, reduces bandwidth consumption, and enhances real-time responsiveness for applications.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Edge nodes may also be resource-constrained devices, limiting the choice in terms of security methods.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Moreover, a shift from centralized top-down infrastructure to a decentralized trust model is required.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] On the other hand, by keeping and processing data at the edge, it is possible to increase privacy by minimizing the transmission of sensitive information to the cloud.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Furthermore, the ownership of collected data shifts from service providers to end-users.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Scalability in a distributed network must face different issues.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] First, it must take into account the heterogeneity of the devices, having different performance and energy constraints, the highly dynamic condition, and the reliability of the connections compared to more robust infrastructure of cloud data centers.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Moreover, security requirements may introduce further latency in the communication between nodes, which may slow down the scaling process.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] The state-of-the-art scheduling technique can increase the effective utilization of edge resources and scales the edge server by assigning minimum edge resources to each offloaded task.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Management of failovers is crucial in order to keep a service alive.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] If a single node goes down and is unreachable, users should still be able to access a service without interruptions.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Moreover, edge computing systems must provide actions to recover from a failure and alert the user about the incident.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] To this aim, each device must maintain the network topology of the entire distributed system, so that detection of errors and recovery become easily applicable.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Other factors that may influence this aspect are the connection technologies in use, which may provide different levels of reliability, and the accuracy of the data produced at the edge that could be unreliable due to particular environment conditions.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] As an example, an edge computing device, such as a voice assistant, may continue to provide service to local users even during cloud service or internet outages.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Edge computing brings analytical computational resources close to the end users and therefore can increase the responsiveness and throughput of applications.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] A well-designed edge platform would significantly outperform a traditional cloud-based system.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Some applications rely on short response times, making edge computing a significantly more feasible option than cloud computing.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Examples range from IoT to autonomous driving, anything health or human / public safety relevant, or involving human perception such as facial recognition, which typically takes a human between 370-620 ms to perform.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Edge computing is more likely to be able to mimic the same perception speed as humans, which is useful in applications such as augmented reality, where the headset should preferably recognize who a person is at the same time as the wearer does.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Due to the nearness of the analytical resources to the end users, sophisticated analytical tools and artificial intelligence tools can run on the edge of the system.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] This placement at the edge helps to increase operational efficiency and is responsible for many advantages to the system.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] In distributed AI systems on the edge, data compression is increasingly recognized as a foundational design layer to mitigate bandwidth constraints caused by the exchange of large models and high-resolution sensor streams.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] By using servers located on a local edge network to perform those computations, the video files only need to be transmitted in the local network.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Avoiding transmission over the internet results in significant bandwidth savings and therefore increases efficiency.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] If the recognition is performed locally, it is possible to send the recognized text to the cloud rather than audio recordings, significantly reducing the amount of required bandwidth.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Edge application services reduce the volumes of data that must be moved, the consequent traffic, and the distance that data must travel.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] That provides lower latency and reduces transmission costs.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Computation offloading for real-time applications, such as facial recognition algorithms, showed considerable improvements in response times, as demonstrated in early research.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Further research showed that using resource-rich machines called cloudlets or micro data centers near mobile users, which offer services typically found in the cloud, provided improvements in execution time when some of the tasks are offloaded to the edge node.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] On the other hand, offloading every task may result in a slowdown due to transfer times between device and nodes, so depending on the workload, an optimal configuration can be defined.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] An IoT-based power grid system enables communication of electricity and data to monitor and control the power grid, which makes energy management more efficient.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] Other notable applications include connected cars, self-driving cars, smart cities, Industry 4.0, home automation, missiles,, satellite systems , as well as frameworks such as MediaPipe.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/edge-computing] The growing field of **edge artificial intelligence** (edge AI or edge intelligence, sometimes referred to as "local AI" or "on-device AI") implements artificial intelligence in an edge computing environment, on the device or close to where data is collected.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] In 2011, the need to extend cloud computing with fog computing emerged, in order to cope with huge number of IoT (Internet of Things) devices and big data volumes for real-time low-latency applications.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] Fog computing, much like edge computing, is intended for distributed computing where numerous "peripheral" devices connect to a cloud.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] The word "fog" refers to its cloud-like properties, but closer to the "ground", i.e.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] An additional benefit is that the processed data is most likely to be needed by the same devices that generated the data, so that by processing locally rather than remotely, the latency between input and response is minimized.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] This idea is not entirely new: in non-cloud-computing scenarios, special-purpose hardware (e.g., signal-processing chips performing fast Fourier transforms) has long been used to reduce latency and reduce the burden on a CPU.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] Fog networking consists of a control plane and a data plane.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] For example, on the data plane, fog computing enables computing services to reside at the edge of the network as opposed to servers in a data-center.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] Fog networking supports the Internet of Things (IoT) concept, in which most of the devices used by humans on a daily basis will be connected to each other.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] Examples include phones, wearable health monitoring devices, connected vehicle and augmented reality using devices such as the Google Glass.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] IoT devices are often resource-constrained and have limited computational abilities to perform cryptography computations.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] A fog node can provide security for IoT devices by performing these cryptographic computations instead.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] SPAWAR, a division of the US Navy, is prototyping and testing a scalable, secure Disruption Tolerant Mesh Network to protect strategic military assets, both stationary and mobile.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] Machine-control applications, running on the mesh nodes, "take over", when Internet connectivity is lost.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] Use cases include Internet of Things e.g. smart drone swarms.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] The University of Melbourne is addressing the challenges of collecting and processing data from cameras, ECG devices, laptops, smartphones, and IoT devices with its project FogBus 2, which uses edge/fog and Oracle Cloud Infrastructure to process data in real-time.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] ISO/IEC 20248 provides a method whereby the data of objects identified by edge computing using Automated Identification Data Carriers (AIDC), a barcode and/or RFID tag, can be read, interpreted, verified and made available into the "Fog" and on the "Edge," even when the AIDC tag has moved on.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] The term "fog computing" was first developed by Cisco in 2012.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] November 19, 2015, Cisco Systems, ARM Holdings, Dell, Intel, Microsoft, and Princeton University, founded the OpenFog Consortium to promote interests and development in fog computing.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] Managing-Director Helder Antunes became the consortium's first chairman and Intel's Chief IoT Strategist Jeff Fedders became its first president.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] Both cloud computing and fog computing provide storage, applications, and data to end-users.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] However, fog computing is closer to end-users and has wider geographical distribution.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] 'Cloud computing' is the practice of using a network of remote servers hosted on the Internet to store, manage, and process data, rather than a local server or a personal computer.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] Also known as edge computing or fogging, fog computing facilitates the operation of compute, storage, and networking services between end devices and cloud computing data centers.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] This paradigm supports vertically-isolated, latency-sensitive applications by providing ubiquitous, scalable, layered, federated, distributed computing, storage, and network connectivity.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] Thus, fog computing is most distinguished by distance from the edge.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] In the theoretical model of fog computing, fog computing nodes are physically and functionally operative between edge nodes and centralized cloud.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] Much of the terminology is undefined, including key architectural terms like "smart", and the distinction between fog computing from edge computing is not generally agreed.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] While edge computing is typically referred to the location where services are instantiated, fog computing implies distribution of the communication, computation, storage resources, and services on or close to devices and systems in the control of end-users.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] Fog computing is a medium weight and intermediate level of computing power.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] Rather than a substitute, fog computing often serves as a complement to cloud computing.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] Fog computing is more energy-efficient than cloud computing.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/fog-computing] IEEE adopted the fog computing standards proposed by OpenFog Consortium.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The field has evolved due to the convergence of multiple technologies, including ubiquitous computing, sensors, embedded systems, and machine learning.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Traditional fields of embedded systems, wireless sensor networks, control systems, and automation independently and collectively enable the Internet of things.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] While in the consumer market, IoT technology is most commonly as smart home products—including devices and appliances like thermostats and smart speakers—the technology's largest applications are in the business and industrial sectors.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Commercial asset tracking and fleet management represent the largest single application of IoT, accounting for 22% of the total market, driven by the need to monitor mobile assets like vehicles and shipping containers.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The largest asset tracking sub-segments in transport & logistics are trailer and intermodal container tracking, reaching 5.8 million and 5.3 million active devices globally at the end of 2024 respectively.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Other major applications include industrial monitoring, smart metering in utilities, and connected healthcare.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Due to their interconnected nature, IoT devices are vulnerable to security breaches and privacy concerns.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] At the same time, the way these devices communicate wirelessly creates regulatory ambiguities, complicating jurisdictional boundaries of the data transfer.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Around 1972, for its remote site use, the Stanford Artificial Intelligence Laboratory developed a computer-controlled vending machine, adapted from a machine rented from Canteen Vending, which sold for cash or, through a computer terminal (Teletype Model 33 KSR), on credit.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Amongst its products were beer, yogurt, and milk.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] It was named *Prancing Pony*, after the name of the room, which was named after an inn in J.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Tolkien's epic fantasy novel The Lord of the Rings.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] A successor version still operates in the Computer Science Department at Stanford, with updated hardware and software.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] While it was initially accessible only on the CMU campus, it gained prominence as the first ARPANET-connected appliance.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Mark Weiser's 1991 paper on ubiquitous computing, "The Computer of the 21st Century", as well as academic venues such as UbiComp and PerCom, produced the contemporary vision of the IoT.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The field gained momentum when Bill Joy envisioned device-to-device communication as part of his "Six Webs" framework, which was presented at the World Economic Forum in Davos in 1999.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The concept of the "Internet of things" and the term itself first appeared in a speech by Peter T.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Lewis to the Congressional Black Caucus Foundation 15th Annual Legislative Weekend in Washington, D.C., published in September 1985.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The primary defining characteristic of the Internet of things has been considered its ability to embed short-range mobile transceivers in various gadgets and daily necessities, enabling new forms of communication between people and things, as well as between things themselves.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Defining the Internet of things as "simply the point in time when more 'things or objects' were connected to the Internet than people", Cisco Systems estimated that the IoT was "born" between 2008 and 2009, with the things/people ratio growing from 0.08 in 2003 to 1.84 in 2010.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The extensive set of applications for IoT devices is often divided into consumer, commercial, industrial, and infrastructure spaces.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] A growing portion of IoT devices is created for consumer use, including connected vehicles, home automation, wearable technology, connected health, and appliances with remote monitoring capabilities.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices are part of the broader concept of home automation, which generally includes lighting, heating and air conditioning, media and security systems, and camera systems.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Moreover, long-term benefits could include energy savings by automatically ensuring lights and electronics are turned off or by making the residents in the home aware of usage.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] A smart home, also known as an automated home, could be based on a platform or hubs that control smart devices and appliances.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] For instance, using Apple's HomeKit, manufacturers can have their home products and accessories controlled by an application in iOS devices such as the iPhone and the Apple Watch.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] This could be a dedicated app or iOS native applications such as Siri.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] This can be demonstrated in the case of Lenovo's Smart Home Essentials, which is a line of smart home devices that are controlled through Apple's Home app or Siri without the need for a Wi-Fi bridge.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] There are also dedicated smart home hubs that are offered as standalone platforms to connect different smart home products.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] These include the Amazon Echo, Google Home, Apple's HomePod, and Samsung's SmartThings Hub.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] In addition to the commercial systems, there are many non-proprietary, open source ecosystems, including Home Assistant, OpenHAB, and Domoticz.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] One key application of a smart home is to assist the elderly and individuals with disabilities.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] These home systems use assistive technology to accommodate an owner's specific disabilities.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Voice control can assist users with sight and mobility limitations while alert systems can be connected directly to cochlear implants worn by individuals with hearing impairments.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] They can also be equipped with additional safety features, including sensors that monitor for medical emergencies such as falls or seizures.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Smart home technology applied in this way can provide users with more freedom and a higher quality of life.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The term "Enterprise IoT" refers to devices used in business and corporate settings.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The **Internet of Medical Things** (**IoMT**) is an application of the IoT for medical and health-related purposes, data collection and analysis for research, and monitoring.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The IoMT has been referenced as "Smart Healthcare", as the technology for creating a digitized healthcare system, connecting available medical resources and healthcare services.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can be used to enable remote health monitoring and emergency notification systems.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] These health monitoring devices can range from blood pressure and heart rate monitors to advanced devices capable of monitoring specialized implants, such as pacemakers, Fitbit electronic wristbands, or advanced hearing aids.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Some hospitals have begun implementing "smart beds" that can detect when they are occupied and when a patient is attempting to get up.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] It can also adjust itself to ensure appropriate pressure and support are applied to the patient without the manual interaction of nurses.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Specialized sensors can also be equipped within living spaces to monitor the health and general well-being of senior citizens, while ensuring that proper treatment is administered and assisting people in regaining lost mobility via therapy as well.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] These sensors create a network of intelligent sensors that are able to collect, process, transfer, and analyze valuable information in different environments, such as connecting in-home monitoring devices to hospital-based systems.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Other consumer devices to encourage healthy living, such as connected scales or wearable heart monitors, are also a possibility with the IoT.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] End-to-end health monitoring IoT platforms are also available for antenatal and chronic patients, helping one manage health vitals and recurring medication requirements.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Advances in plastic and fabric electronics fabrication methods have enabled ultra-low-cost, use-and-throw IoMT sensors.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] These sensors, along with the required radio-frequency identification electronics, can be fabricated on paper or e-textiles for wireless powered disposable sensing devices.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Applications have been established for point-of-care medical diagnostics, where portability and low system complexity are considered essential.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] As of 2018, IoMT was being applied in the clinical laboratory industry.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] IoMT in the insurance industry provides access to better and new types of dynamic information.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] This includes sensor-based solutions such as biosensors, wearables, connected health devices, and mobile apps to track customer behavior.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] This can lead to more accurate underwriting and new pricing models.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The application of the IoT in healthcare plays a fundamental role in managing chronic diseases and in disease prevention and control.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Remote monitoring is made possible through the connection of wireless solutions.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The connectivity enables health practitioners to capture patients' data and apply algorithms in health data analysis.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can assist in the integration of communications, control, and information processing across various transportation systems.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Application of the IoT extends to all aspects of transportation systems (i.e., the vehicle, the infrastructure, and the driver or user).
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Dynamic interaction between these components of a transport system enables inter- and intra-vehicular communication, smart traffic control, smart parking, electronic toll collection systems, logistics and fleet management, vehicle control, safety, and road assistance.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] In vehicle security applications, IoT-connected GPS trackers can operate for months or years on internal batteries, using low-power wide-area network protocols such as LTE-M to transmit location data to owners via smartphone applications when unauthorized movement is detected.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] In vehicular communication systems, vehicle-to-everything communication (V2X), consists of three main components: vehicle-to-vehicle communication (V2V), vehicle-to-infrastructure communication (V2I), and vehicle-to-pedestrian communication (V2P).
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Eventually, V2X is the first step to autonomous driving and connected road infrastructure.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can be used to monitor and control the mechanical, electrical, and electronic systems used in various types of buildings (e.g., public and private, industrial, institutions, or residential) in home automation and building automation systems.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Also known as IIoT, industrial IoT devices acquire and analyze data from connected equipment, operational technology (OT), locations, and people.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Combined with operational technology (OT) monitoring devices, IIoT helps regulate and monitor industrial systems.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Additionally, the same implementation can be carried out for automated record updates of asset placement in industrial storage units as the size of the assets can vary from a small screw to the whole motor spare part, and misplacement of such assets can cause a loss of manpower time and money.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can connect various manufacturing devices equipped with sensing, identification, processing, communication, actuation, and networking capabilities.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Network control and management of manufacturing equipment, asset and situation management, or manufacturing process control enable IoT to be utilized for industrial applications and smart manufacturing.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] IoT intelligent systems enable rapid manufacturing and optimization of new products and rapid response to product demands.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Digital control systems, which aim to automate process controls, operator tools, and service information systems, alongside optimizing plant safety and security, fall within the purview of the IIoT.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Furthermore, IoT can also be applied to asset management via predictive maintenance, statistical evaluation, and measurements to maximize reliability.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Industrial management systems can be integrated with smart grids, enabling energy optimization.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Measurements, automated controls, plant optimization, health and safety management, and other functions are provided by networked sensors.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] In addition to general manufacturing, IoT is also used for processes in the industrialization of construction.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] There are numerous IoT applications in farming such as collecting data on temperature, rainfall, humidity, wind speed, pest infestation, and soil content.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] This data can be used to automate farming techniques, make informed decisions to improve quality and quantity, minimize risk and waste, and reduce the effort required to manage crops.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] For example, farmers can now monitor soil temperature and moisture from afar and even apply IoT-acquired data to precision fertilization programs.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The overall goal is that data from sensors, coupled with the farmer's knowledge and intuition about his or her farm, can help increase farm productivity, and also help reduce costs.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] In August 2018, Toyota Tsusho began a partnership with Microsoft to create fish farming tools using the Microsoft Azure application suite for IoT technologies related to water management.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Developed in part by researchers from Kindai University, the water pump mechanisms use artificial intelligence to count the number of fish on a conveyor belt, analyze the number of fish, and deduce the effectiveness of water flow from the data the fish provide.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The FarmBeats project from Microsoft Research that uses TV white space to connect farms is also a part of the Azure Marketplace now.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices are in use to monitor the environments and systems of boats and yachts.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Many pleasure boats are left unattended for days in summer, and months in winter so such devices provide valuable early alerts of boat flooding, fire, and deep discharge of batteries.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Monitoring and controlling operations of sustainable urban and rural infrastructures like bridges, railway tracks and on- and offshore wind farms is a key application of the IoT.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT infrastructure can be used for monitoring any events or changes in structural conditions that can compromise safety and increase risk.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can benefit the construction industry by cost-saving, time reduction, better quality workday, paperless workflow and increase in productivity.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] It can help in making faster decisions and saving money in Real-Time Data Analytics.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] It can also be used for scheduling repair and maintenance activities efficiently, by coordinating tasks between different service providers and users of these facilities.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can also be used to control critical infrastructure, like bridges, to provide access to ships.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The usage of IoT devices for monitoring and operating infrastructure is likely to significantly improve incident management and emergency response coordination, and quality of service, up-times and reduce costs of operation in all infrastructure-related areas.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Even areas such as waste management can benefit.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] There are several planned or ongoing large-scale deployments of the IoT to enable better management of cities and systems.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] For example, Songdo, South Korea, the first fully equipped and wired smart city, is gradually being built, with approximately 70 percent of the business district completed as of June 2018.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] A sizeable portion of the city, the first of its kind, is planned to be wired and automated to operate with little or no human intervention.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] In 2014, another application was undergoing a project in Santander, Spain.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] For this deployment, two approaches have been adopted.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] This city of 180,000 inhabitants has already seen 18,000 downloads of its city smartphone app.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The app is connected to 10,000 sensors that enable services like parking search and environmental monitoring.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Additionally, city context information is used in this deployment, aiming to benefit merchants through a spark deals mechanism based on city behavior that aims at maximizing the impact of each notification.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Other examples of large-scale deployments underway include the Sino-Singapore Guangzhou Knowledge City; work on improving air and water quality, reducing noise pollution, and increasing transportation efficiency in San Jose, California; and smart traffic management in western Singapore.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Using its RPMA (Random Phase Multiple Access) technology, San Diego–based Ingenu has built a nationwide public network for low-bandwidth data transmissions using the same unlicensed 2.4 gigahertz spectrum as Wi-Fi.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Ingenu's "Machine Network" covers more than a third of the US population across 35 major cities including San Diego and Dallas.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] French company, Sigfox, commenced building an Ultra Narrowband wireless data network in the San Francisco Bay Area in 2014, the first business to achieve such a deployment in the U.S.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] It subsequently announced it would set up a total of 4000 base stations to cover a total of 30 cities in the U.S. by the end of 2016, making it the largest IoT network coverage provider in the country thus far.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Cisco also participates in smart cities projects.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Cisco has deployed technologies for Smart Wi-Fi, Smart Safety & Security, Smart Lighting, Smart Parking, Smart Transports, Smart Bus Stops, Smart Kiosks, Remote Expert for Government Services (REGS) and Smart Education in the five km area in the city of Vijayawada, India.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Another example of a large deployment is the one completed by New York Waterways in New York City to connect all the city's vessels and be able to monitor them live 24/7.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The network was designed and engineered by Fluidmesh Networks, a Chicago-based company developing wireless networks for critical applications.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The NYWW network is currently providing coverage on the Hudson River, East River, and Upper New York Bay.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] With the wireless network in place, NY Waterway is able to take control of its fleet and passengers in a way that was not previously possible.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] New applications can include security, energy and fleet management, digital signage, public Wi-Fi, paperless ticketing and others.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Significant numbers of energy-consuming devices (e.g., lamps, household appliances, motors, pumps, etc.) already integrate Internet connectivity, which can allow them to communicate with utilities not only to balance power generation but also helps optimize the energy consumption as a whole.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] These devices allow for remote control by users, or central management via a cloud-based interface, and enable functions like scheduling (e.g., remotely powering on or off heating systems, controlling ovens, changing lighting conditions etc.).
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The smart grid is a utility-side IoT application; systems gather and act on energy and power-related information to improve the efficiency of the production and distribution of electricity.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Using advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) Internet-connected devices, electric utilities not only collect data from end-users, but also manage distribution automation devices like transformers.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Environmental monitoring applications of the IoT typically use sensors to assist in environmental protection by monitoring air or water quality, atmospheric or soil conditions, and can even include areas like monitoring the movements of wildlife and their habitats.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Development of resource-constrained devices connected to the Internet also means that other applications like earthquake or tsunami early-warning systems can also be used by emergency services to provide more effective aid.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices in this application typically span a large geographic area and can also be mobile.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] It has been argued that the standardization that IoT brings to wireless sensing will revolutionize this area.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Another example of integrating the IoT is the concept of a "living lab." Living labs integrate and combine research and innovation processes, establishing within a public-private-people-partnership.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Between 2006 and January 2024, there were over 440 living labs (though not all are currently active) that use the IoT to collaborate and share knowledge between stakeholders to co-create innovative and technological products.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] When companies intend to implement and develop IoT services for smart cities, they need to have economic incentives.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The US government plays a key role in smart city projects; changes in policies will help cities to implement the IoT, which provides effectiveness, efficiency, and accuracy of the resources that are being used.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The Internet of Military Things (IoMT) is the application of IoT technologies in the military domain for the purposes of reconnaissance, surveillance, and other combat-related objectives.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] It is heavily influenced by the future prospects of warfare in an urban environment and involves the use of sensors, munitions, vehicles, robots, human-wearable biometrics, and other smart technology that is relevant on the battlefield.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] One of the examples of IOT devices used in the military is the Xaver 1000 system.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The Xaver 1000 was developed by Israel's Camero Tech, which is the latest in the company's line of "through-wall imaging systems." The Xaver line uses millimeter wave (MMW) radar, or radar in the range of 30-300 gigahertz.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] It is equipped with an AI-based life target tracking system as well as its own 3D 'sense-through-the-wall' technology.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The **Internet of Battlefield Things** (**IoBT**) is a project initiated and executed by the U.S.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) that focuses on the basic science related to the IoT that enhances the capabilities of Army soldiers.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] In 2017, ARL launched the Internet of Battlefield Things Collaborative Research Alliance (IoBT-CRA), establishing a working collaboration between industry, university, and Army researchers to advance the theoretical foundations of IoT technologies and their applications to Army operations.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The **Ocean of Things** project is a DARPA-led program designed to establish an Internet of things across large ocean areas for the purposes of collecting, monitoring, and analyzing environmental and vessel activity data.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The project entails the deployment of about 50,000 floats that house a passive sensor suite that autonomously detects and tracks military and commercial vessels as part of a cloud-based network.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] There are several applications of smart or active packaging in which a QR code or NFC tag is affixed to a product or its packaging.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The tag itself is passive; however, it contains a unique identifier (typically a URL) which enables a user to access digital content about the product via a smartphone.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Strictly speaking, such passive items are not part of the Internet of things, but they can be seen as enablers of digital interactions.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The term "Internet of Packaging" has been coined to describe applications in which unique identifiers are used, to automate supply chains, and are scanned on large scale by consumers to access digital content.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Authentication of the unique identifiers, and thereby of the product itself, is possible via a copy-sensitive digital watermark or copy detection pattern for scanning when scanning a QR code, while NFC tags can encrypt communication.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] In the Internet of Things (IoT), As of April 2026, the number of devices connected and controlled via the Internet has increased.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Applications of IoT technology vary across devices, but many share common characteristics.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT creates opportunities for more direct integration of the physical world into computer-based systems, resulting in efficiency improvements, economic benefits, and reduced human exertions.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] IoT Analytics reported there were 16.6 billion IoT devices connected in 2023.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] In 2020, the same firm projected there would be 30 billion devices connected by 2025.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] As of October, 2024, there are around 17 billion.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Ambient intelligence and autonomous control are not part of the original concept of the Internet of things.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Ambient intelligence and autonomous control do not necessarily require Internet structures, either.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] However, there is a shift in research (by companies such as Intel) to integrate the concepts of the IoT and autonomous control, with initial outcomes towards this direction considering objects as the driving force for autonomous IoT.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] An approach in this context is deep reinforcement learning where most of IoT systems provide a dynamic and interactive environment.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Training an agent (i.e., IoT device) to behave smartly in such an environment cannot be addressed by conventional machine learning algorithms such as supervised learning.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Through a reinforcement learning approach, a learning agent can sense the environment's state (e.g., sensing home temperature), perform actions (e.g., turn HVAC on or off) and learn by maximizing accumulated rewards it receives.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] IoT intelligence can be offered at three levels: IoT devices, Edge/Fog nodes, and cloud computing.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The need for intelligent control and decision at each level depends on the time sensitiveness of the IoT application.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] For example, an autonomous vehicle's camera needs to make real-time obstacle detection to avoid an accident.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] This fast decision making would not be possible if it is necessary to transfer data from the vehicle to cloud instances and return the predictions back to the vehicle.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Instead, the operation should be performed locally in the vehicle.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Integrating advanced machine learning algorithms, including deep learning, into IoT devices is an active research area to make smart objects closer to reality.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Moreover, it is possible to get the most value out of IoT deployments through analyzing IoT data, extracting hidden information, and predicting control decisions.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] A wide variety of machine learning techniques have been used in IoT domain ranging from traditional methods such as regression, support vector machine, and random forest to advanced ones such as convolutional neural networks, LSTM, and variational autoencoder.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Modern IoT products and solutions in the marketplace use a variety of different technologies to support such context-aware automation, but more sophisticated forms of intelligence are requested to permit sensor units and intelligent cyber-physical systems to be deployed in real environments.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] IoT system architecture, in its simplistic view, consists of three tiers: Tier 1: Devices, Tier 2: the Edge Gateway, and Tier 3: the Cloud.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Devices include networked things, such as the sensors and actuators found in IoT equipment, particularly those that use protocols such as Modbus, Bluetooth, Zigbee, or proprietary protocols, to connect to an Edge Gateway.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The Edge Gateway layer consists of sensor data aggregation systems called Edge Gateways that provide functionality, such as pre-processing of the data, securing connectivity to cloud, using systems such as WebSockets, the event hub, and, even in some cases, edge analytics or fog computing.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Edge Gateway layer is also required to give a common view of the devices to the upper layers to facilitate in easier management.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The final tier includes the cloud application built for IoT using the microservices architecture, which are usually polyglot and inherently secure in nature using HTTPS/OAuth.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] It includes various database systems that store sensor data, such as time series databases or asset stores using backend data storage systems (e.g.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The cloud tier in most cloud-based IoT system features event queuing and messaging system that handles communication that transpires in all tiers.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Some experts classified the three-tiers in the IoT system as edge, platform, and enterprise and these are connected by proximity network, access network, and service network, respectively.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] IoT requires huge scalability in the network space to handle the surge of devices.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] IETF 6LoWPAN can be used to connect devices to IP networks.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] With billions of devices being added to the Internet space, IPv6 may play an important role in handling the network layer scalability.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] IETF's Constrained Application Protocol, ZeroMQ, and MQTT can provide lightweight data transport.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] In practice, many groups of IoT devices are hidden behind gateway nodes and may not have unique addresses.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Also, the vision of everything being interconnected is not needed for most applications as it is mainly the data that needs interconnecting at a higher layer.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Fog computing is a viable alternative to prevent such a large burst of data flow through the Internet.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The edge devices' computation power to analyze and process data is extremely limited.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Limited processing power is a key attribute of IoT devices as their purpose is to supply data about physical objects while remaining autonomous.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Heavy processing requirements use more battery power, harming IoT's ability to operate.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Scalability is easy because IoT devices simply supply data through the Internet to a server with sufficient processing power.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Performance is improved, especially for huge IoT systems with millions of nodes.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Conventional IoT is connected via a mesh network and led by a major head node (centralized controller).
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The head node decides how a data is created, stored, and transmitted.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] In contrast, decentralized IoT attempts to divide IoT systems into smaller divisions.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The head node authorizes partial decision-making power to lower level sub-nodes under mutual agreed policy.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Some approaches to decentralized IoT attempt to address the limited bandwidth and hashing capacity of battery-powered or wireless IoT devices via blockchain.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] In semi-open or closed loops (i.e., value chains, whenever a global finality can be settled) the IoT is often analyzed as a complex system due to the large number of different interactions between autonomous actors, and its capacity to integrate new actors.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] At the overall stage (full open loop) it will likely be seen as a chaotic environment (since systems always have finality).
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] As a practical approach, not all elements on the Internet of things run in a global, public space.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Subsystems are often implemented to mitigate the risks of privacy, control and reliability.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] For example, domestic robotics (domotics) running inside a smart home might only share data within and be available via a local network.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Managing and controlling a high dynamic ad hoc IoT things/devices network is a complex task within traditional network architecture, software-defined networking (SDN) provides a dynamic approach that better fits the special requirements of IoT applications.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The exact scale of the Internet of things is unknown, with quotes of billions or trillions often quoted at the beginning of IoT articles.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] In 2015, there were 83 million smart devices in people's homes.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] This number is expected to grow to 193 million devices by 2020.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] In 2023, the number of connected IoT devices will reach 16.6 billion.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] The number of online-capable devices grew 31% from 2016 to 2017 to reach 8.4 billion.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] In the Internet of things, the precise geographic location of a thing—and also the precise geographic dimensions of a thing—can be critical.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] (Note that some things on the Internet of things will be sensors, and sensor location is usually important.) The GeoWeb and Digital Earth are applications that become possible when things can become organized and connected by location.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] However, the challenges that remain include the constraints of variable spatial scales, the need to handle massive amounts of data, and an indexing for fast search and neighbour operations.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] On the Internet of things, if things are able to take actions on their own initiative, this human-centric mediation role is eliminated.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Thus, the time-space context that we as humans take for granted must be given a central role in this information ecosystem.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Just as standards play a key role on the Internet and the Web, geo-spatial standards will play a key role on the Internet of things.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Many IoT devices have the potential to take a piece of this market.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] For improved user interaction, some technology leaders are joining forces to create standards for communication between devices to solve this problem.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Others are turning to the concept of predictive interaction of devices, "where collected data is used to predict and trigger actions on the specific devices" while making them work together.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Social Internet of things (SIoT) is a new kind of IoT that focuses on the importance of social interaction and relationships between IoT devices.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] IoT defines a device with an identity like a citizen in a community and connects them to the Internet to provide services to its users.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT defines a social network for IoT devices only to interact with each other for different goals that to serve human.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT is different from the original IoT in terms of the collaboration characteristics.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] IoT is passive; it was set to serve for dedicated purposes with existing IoT devices in a predetermined system.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT is active, it was programmed and managed by AI to serve for unplanned purposes with mix and match of potential IoT devices from different systems that benefit its users.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices with built-in sociability are able to broadcast their abilities or functionality, which can be used to discover and share information with other IoT devices in the same or nearby network, realizing SIoT.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Facilitating further functionality with these abilities could be helpful during emergencies.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] IoT sensors on the vehicles, road and traffic lights monitor the conditions of the vehicles and drivers and alert when attention is needed, and also coordinate themselves automatically to ensure autonomous driving is working normally.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] If a crash happens, the IoT camera will inform the nearest hospital and police station for help.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] System security is always a concern for any technology, and it is more crucial for SIoT as not only the security of oneself needs to be considered, but also the mutual trust mechanism between collaborative IoT devices from time to time, from place to place.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] Another critical challenge for SIoT is the accuracy and reliability of the sensors.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p01] In most circumstances, IoT sensors would need to respond quickly to avoid accidents, injury, and loss of life.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] There are many technologies that enable the IoT.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The original idea of the Auto-ID Center is based on RFID tags and distinct identification through the Electronic Product Code.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] This has evolved into objects having an IP address or URI.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] An alternative view, from the world of the Semantic Web focuses instead on making all things (not just those electronic, smart, or RFID-enabled) addressable by the existing naming protocols, such as URI.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The objects themselves do not converse, but they may now be referred to by other agents, such as powerful centralised servers acting for their human owners.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Integration with the Internet implies that devices will use an IP address as a distinct identifier.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Due to the limited address space of IPv4 (which allows for 4.3 billion different addresses), objects in the IoT will have to use the next generation of the Internet protocol (IPv6) to scale to the extremely large address space required.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Internet-of-things devices additionally will benefit from the stateless address auto-configuration present in IPv6, as it reduces the configuration overhead on the hosts, and the IETF 6LoWPAN header compression.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] To a large extent, the future of the Internet of things will not be possible without the support of IPv6; and consequently, the global adoption of IPv6 in the coming years will be critical for the successful development of the IoT in the future.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Different technologies have different roles in a protocol stack.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] This is a list of technical standards for the IoT, most of which are open standards, and the standards organizations that aspire to successfully setting them.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Some scholars and activists argue that the IoT can be used to create new models of civic engagement if device networks can be open to user control and interoperable platforms.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Howard, a professor and author, writes that political life in both democracies and authoritarian regimes will be shaped by the way the IoT will be used for civic engagement.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] For that to happen, he argues that any connected device should be able to divulge a list of the "ultimate beneficiaries" of its sensor data and that individual citizens should be able to add new organisations to the beneficiary list.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] In addition, he argues that civil society groups need to start developing their IoT strategy for making use of data and engaging with the public.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] One of the key drivers of the IoT is data.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The success of the idea of connecting devices to make them more efficient is dependent upon access to and storage & processing of data.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] For this purpose, companies working on the IoT collect data from multiple sources and store it in their cloud network for further processing.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] This leaves the door wide open for privacy and security dangers and single point vulnerability of multiple systems.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The other issues pertain to consumer choice and ownership of data and how it is used.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Though still in their infancy, regulations and governance regarding these issues of privacy, security, and data ownership continue to develop.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Some examples of legislation that is relevant to privacy and data collection are: the US Privacy Act of 1974, OECD Guidelines on the Protection of Privacy and Transborder Flows of Personal Data of 1980, and the EU Directive 95/46/EC of 1995.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] However, the FTC stopped at just making recommendations for now.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] A resolution passed by the Senate in March 2015, is already being considered by the Congress.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] This resolution recognized the need for formulating a National Policy on IoT and the matter of privacy, security and spectrum.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Approved on 28 September 2018, California Senate Bill No.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Several standards for the IoT industry are actually being established relating to automobiles because most concerns arising from use of connected cars apply to healthcare devices as well.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] In fact, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) is preparing cybersecurity guidelines and a database of best practices to make automotive computer systems more secure.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] A recent report from the World Bank examines the challenges and opportunities in government adoption of IoT.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] In early December 2021, the U.K. government introduced the Product Security and Telecommunications Infrastructure bill (PST), an effort to legislate IoT distributors, manufacturers, and importers to meet certain cybersecurity standards.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The bill also seeks to improve the security credentials of consumer IoT devices.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] For example, wireless connectivity for IoT devices can be done using Bluetooth, Wi-Fi, Wi-Fi HaLow, Zigbee, Z-Wave, LoRa, NB-IoT, Cat M1 as well as completely custom proprietary radios – each with its own advantages and disadvantages; and unique support ecosystem.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The IoT's amorphous computing nature is also a problem for security, since patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-price devices.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] One set of researchers says that the failure of vendors to support older devices with patches and updates leaves more than 87% of active Android devices vulnerable.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Howard, a professor and author, writes that the Internet of things offers immense potential for empowering citizens, making government transparent, and broadening information access.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Howard cautions, however, that privacy threats are enormous, as is the potential for social control and political manipulation.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Concerns about privacy have led many to consider the possibility that big data infrastructures such as the Internet of things and data mining are inherently incompatible with privacy.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Key challenges of increased digitalization in the water, transport or energy sector are related to privacy and cybersecurity which necessitate an adequate response from research and policymakers alike.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Writer Adam Greenfield claims that IoT technologies are not only an invasion of public space but are also being used to perpetuate normative behavior, citing an instance of billboards with hidden cameras that tracked the demographics of passersby who stopped to read the advertisement.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The Internet of Things Council compared the increased prevalence of digital surveillance due to the Internet of things to the concept of the panopticon described by Jeremy Bentham in the 18th century.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The assertion is supported by the works of French philosophers Michel Foucault and Gilles Deleuze.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] In *Discipline and Punish: The Birth of the Prison*, Foucault asserts that the panopticon was a central element of the discipline society developed during the Industrial Era.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Foucault also argued that the discipline systems established in factories and school reflected Bentham's vision of panopticism.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] In his 1992 paper "Postscripts on the Societies of Control", Deleuze wrote that the discipline society had transitioned into a control society, with the computer replacing the panopticon as an instrument of discipline and control while still maintaining the qualities similar to that of panopticism.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Peter-Paul Verbeek, a professor of philosophy of technology at the University of Twente, Netherlands, writes that technology already influences our moral decision making, which in turn affects human agency, privacy and autonomy.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] He cautions against viewing technology merely as a human tool and advocates instead to consider it as an active agent.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Tim O'Reilly believes that the way companies sell IoT devices to consumers is misplaced, disputing the notion that the IoT is about gaining efficiency from putting all kinds of devices online and postulating that, "IoT is really about human augmentation.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Editorials at WIRED have also expressed concern, one stating, "What you're about to lose is your privacy.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) expressed concern regarding the ability of IoT to erode people's control over their own lives.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The ACLU wrote that "There's simply no way to forecast how these immense powers – disproportionately accumulating in the hands of corporations seeking financial advantage and governments craving ever more control – will be used.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] In response to rising concerns about privacy and smart technology, in 2007, the British Government stated it would follow formal Privacy by Design principles when implementing its smart metering program.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The program would lead to the replacement of traditional power meters with smart power meters, which could track and manage energy usage more accurately.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] However the British Computer Society is doubtful these principles were ever actually implemented.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] In 2009, the Dutch Parliament rejected a similar smart metering program, basing their decision on privacy concerns.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The Dutch program later revised and passed in 2011.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] A challenge for producers of IoT applications is to clean, process and interpret the vast amount of data that is gathered by the sensors.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] There is a solution proposed for the analytics of the information referred to as Wireless Sensor Networks.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] These networks share data among sensor nodes that are sent to a distributed system for the analytics of the sensory data.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Another challenge is the storage of this bulk data.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Depending on the application, there could be high data acquisition requirements, which in turn lead to high storage requirements.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] In 2013, the Internet was estimated to be responsible for consuming 5% of the total energy produced, and a "daunting challenge to power" IoT devices to collect and even store data still remains.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Data silos, although a common challenge of legacy systems, still commonly occur with the implementation of IoT devices, particularly within manufacturing.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] As there are a lot of benefits to be gained from IoT and IIoT devices, the means in which the data is stored can present serious challenges without the principles of autonomy, transparency, and interoperability being considered.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The challenges do not occur by the device itself, but the means in which databases and data warehouses are set up.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] These challenges were identified by Keller (2021) when investigating the IT and application landscape of I4.0 implementation within German M&E manufacturers.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Security is the biggest concern in adopting Internet of things technology, with concerns that rapid development is happening without appropriate consideration of the profound security challenges involved and the regulatory changes that might be necessary.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The rapid development of the Internet of Things (IoT) has allowed billions of devices to connect to the network.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Due to too many connected devices and the limitation of communication security technology, various security issues gradually appear in the IoT.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Most of the technical security concerns are similar to those of conventional servers, workstations and smartphones.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] These concerns include using weak authentication, forgetting to change default credentials, unencrypted messages sent between devices, SQL injections, man-in-the-middle attacks, and poor handling of security updates.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] However, many IoT devices have severe operational limitations on the computational power available to them.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] These constraints often make them unable to directly use basic security measures such as implementing firewalls or using strong cryptosystems to encrypt their communications with other devices - and the low price and consumer focus of many devices makes a robust security patching system uncommon.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Rather than conventional security vulnerabilities, fault injection attacks are on the rise and targeting IoT devices.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] A fault injection attack is a physical attack on a device to purposefully introduce faults in the system to change the intended behavior.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Faults might happen unintentionally due to environmental noises and electromagnetic fields.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] There are ideas stemming from control-flow integrity (CFI) to prevent fault injection attacks and system recovery to a healthy state before the fault.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Computer-controlled devices in automobiles such as brakes, engine, locks, hood and trunk releases, horn, heat, and dashboard have been shown to be vulnerable to attackers who have access to the on-board network.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] In some cases, vehicle computer systems are Internet-connected, allowing them to be exploited remotely.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] By 2008, security researchers had shown the ability to remotely control pacemakers without authority.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Later, hackers demonstrated remote control of insulin pumps and implantable cardioverter defibrillators.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Poorly secured Internet-accessible IoT devices can also be subverted to attack others.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] In 2016, a distributed denial of service attack powered by Internet of things devices running the Mirai malware took down a DNS provider and major web sites.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The Mirai Botnet had infected roughly 65,000 IoT devices within the first 20 hours.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Eventually, the infections increased to around 200,000 to 300,000 infections.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Brazil, Colombia and Vietnam made up of 41.5% of the infections.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The Mirai Botnet had singled out specific IoT devices that consisted of DVRs, IP cameras, routers and printers.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] These sorts of attacks have caused security experts to view IoT as a real threat to Internet services.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] National Intelligence Council in an unclassified report maintains that it would be hard to deny "access to networks of sensors and remotely-controlled objects by enemies of the United States, criminals, and mischief makers...
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] An open market for aggregated sensor data could serve the interests of commerce and security no less than it helps criminals and spies identify vulnerable targets.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Thus, massively parallel sensor fusion may undermine social cohesion, if it proves to be fundamentally incompatible with Fourth-Amendment guarantees against unreasonable search." In general, the intelligence community views the Internet of things as a rich source of data.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] There have been a range of responses to concerns over security.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The Internet of Things Security Foundation (IoTSF) was launched on 23 September 2015 with a mission to secure the Internet of things by promoting knowledge and best practices.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Its founding board is made up of technology providers and telecommunications companies.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] In addition, large IT companies are continually developing innovative solutions to ensure the security of IoT devices.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] In 2017, Mozilla launched Project Things, which allows to route IoT devices through a safe Web of Things gateway.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] As per the estimates from KBV Research, the overall IoT security market would grow at 27.9% rate during 2016–2022 as a result of growing infrastructural concerns and diversified usage of Internet of things.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Governmental regulation is argued by some to be necessary to secure IoT devices and the wider Internet – as market incentives to secure IoT devices is insufficient.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] It was found that due to the nature of most of the IoT development boards, they generate predictable and weak keys which make it easy to be utilized by man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] However, various hardening approaches were proposed by many researchers to resolve the issue of SSH weak implementation and weak keys.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] IoT security within the field of manufacturing presents different challenges and varying perspectives.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Within the EU and Germany, data protection is constantly referenced throughout manufacturing and digital policy, particularly that of I4.0.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] However, the attitude towards data security differs from the enterprise perspective, whereas there is an emphasis on less data protection in the form of GDPR, as the data being collected from IoT devices in the manufacturing sector does not display personal details.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Yet, research has indicated that manufacturing experts are concerned about "data security for protecting machine technology from international competitors with the ever-greater push for interconnectivity".
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] IoT systems are typically controlled by event-driven smart apps that take as input either sensed data, user inputs, or other external triggers (from the Internet) and command one or more actuators towards providing different forms of automation.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of sensors include smoke detectors, motion sensors, and contact sensors.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of actuators include smart locks, smart power outlets, and door controls.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Popular control platforms on which third-party developers can build smart apps that interact wirelessly with these sensors and actuators include Samsung's SmartThings, Apple's HomeKit, and Amazon's Alexa, among others.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Detecting flaws that lead to such states, requires a holistic view of installed apps, component devices, their configurations, and more importantly, how they interact.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Recently, researchers from the University of California Riverside have proposed IotSan, a novel practical system that uses model checking as a building block to reveal "interaction-level" flaws by identifying events that can lead the system to unsafe states.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] They have evaluated IotSan on the Samsung SmartThings platform.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] From 76 manually configured systems, IotSan detects 147 vulnerabilities (i.e., violations of safe physical states/properties).
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Given widespread recognition of the evolving nature of the design and management of the Internet of things, sustainable and secure deployment of IoT solutions must design for "anarchic scalability".
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Application of the concept of anarchic scalability can be extended to physical systems (i.e. controlled real-world objects), by virtue of those systems being designed to account for uncertain management futures.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] This hard anarchic scalability thus provides a pathway forward to fully realize the potential of Internet-of-things solutions by selectively constraining physical systems to allow for all management regimes without risking physical failure.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Brown University computer scientist Michael Littman has argued that successful execution of the Internet of things requires consideration of the interface's usability as well as the technology itself.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] A concern regarding Internet-of-things technologies pertains to the environmental impacts of the manufacture, use, and eventual disposal of all these semiconductor-rich devices.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Modern electronics are replete with a wide variety of heavy metals and rare-earth metals, as well as highly toxic synthetic chemicals.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] This makes them extremely difficult to properly recycle.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Electronic components are often incinerated or placed in regular landfills.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Furthermore, the human and environmental cost of mining the rare-earth metals that are integral to modern electronic components continues to grow.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] This leads to societal questions concerning the environmental impacts of IoT devices over their lifetime.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The Electronic Frontier Foundation has raised concerns that companies can use the technologies necessary to support connected devices to intentionally disable or "brick" their customers' devices via a remote software update or by disabling a service necessary to the operation of the device.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] In one example, home automation devices sold with the promise of a "Lifetime Subscription" were rendered useless after Nest Labs acquired Revolv and made the decision to shut down the central servers the Revolv devices had used to operate.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Owners should be free to point their devices to a different server or collaborate on improved software.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] But such action violates the United States DMCA section 1201, which only has an exemption for "local use".
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] This forces tinkerers who want to keep using their own equipment into a legal grey area.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] EFF thinks buyers should refuse electronics and software that prioritize the manufacturer's wishes above their own.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of post-sale manipulations include Google Nest Revolv, disabled privacy settings on Android, Sony disabling Linux on PlayStation 3, and enforced EULA on Wii U.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Kevin Lonergan at *Information Age*, a business technology magazine, has referred to the terms surrounding the IoT as a "terminology zoo".
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The lack of clear terminology is not "useful from a practical point of view" and a "source of confusion for the end user".
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] A company operating in the IoT space could be working in anything related to sensor technology, networking, embedded systems, or analytics.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Regarding IIoT, an industrial sub-field of IoT, the Industrial Internet Consortium's Vocabulary Task Group has created a "common and reusable vocabulary of terms" to ensure "consistent terminology" across publications issued by the Industrial Internet Consortium.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] IoT One has created an IoT Terms Database including a New Term Alert to be notified when a new term is published.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] As of March 2020, this database aggregates 807 IoT-related terms, while keeping material "transparent and comprehensive".
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Despite a shared belief in the potential of the IoT, industry leaders and consumers are facing barriers to adopting IoT technology more widely.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Mike Farley argued in Forbes that while IoT solutions appeal to early adopters, they either lack interoperability or a clear use case for end-users.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] A study by Ericsson regarding the adoption of IoT among Danish companies suggests that many struggle "to pinpoint exactly where the value of IoT lies for them".
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] As for IoT, especially in regard to consumer IoT, information about a user's daily routine is collected so that the "things" around the user can cooperate to provide better services that fulfill personal preferences.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] When the collected information which describes a user in detail travels through multiple hops in a network, due to a diverse integration of services, devices and network, the information stored on a device is vulnerable to privacy violation by compromising nodes existing in an IoT network.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] For example, on 21 October 2016, a multiple distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks systems operated by domain name system provider Dyn, which caused the inaccessibility of several websites, such as GitHub, Twitter, and others.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] This attack is executed through a botnet consisting of a large number of IoT devices including IP cameras, gateways, and even baby monitors.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Information privacy regulations also require organisations to practice "reasonable security".
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] As each organisation's environment is unique, it can prove challenging to demonstrate what "reasonable security" is and what potential risks could be involved for the business.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] According to antivirus provider Kaspersky, there were 639 million data breaches of IoT devices in 2020 and 1.5 billion breaches in the first six months of 2021.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] One method of overcoming the barrier of safety issues is the introduction of standards and certification of devices.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] In 2024, two voluntary and non-competing programs were proposed and launched in the United States: the US Cyber Trust Mark from The Federal Communications Commission and CSA's IoT Device Security Specification from the Connectivity Standards Alliance.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] The programs incorporate international expertise, with the CSA mark recognized by the Singapore Cybersecurity Agency.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Compliance means that IoT devices can resist hacking, control hijacking and theft of confidential data.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Some of these companies risk being "kodaked" – "Kodak was a market leader until digital disruption eclipsed film photography with digital photos" – failing to "see the disruptive forces affecting their industry" and "to truly embrace the new business models the disruptive change opens up".
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] According to a 2018 study, 70–75% of IoT deployments were stuck in the pilot or prototype stage, unable to reach scale due in part to a lack of business planning.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Even though scientists, engineers, and managers across the world are continuously working to create and exploit the benefits of IoT products, there are some flaws in the governance, management and implementation of such projects.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Despite tremendous forward momentum in the field of information and other underlying technologies, IoT still remains a complex area and the problem of how IoT projects are managed still needs to be addressed.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] IoT projects must be run differently than simple and traditional IT, manufacturing or construction projects.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/internet-of-things-p02] Because IoT projects have longer project timelines, a lack of skilled resources and several security/legal issues, there is a need for new and specifically designed project processes.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Latency is physically a consequence of the limited velocity at which any physical interaction can propagate.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] The magnitude of this velocity is always less than or equal to the speed of light.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Therefore, every physical system with any physical separation (distance) between cause and effect will experience some sort of latency, regardless of the nature of the stimulation to which it has been exposed.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] The precise definition of latency depends on the system being observed or the nature of the simulation.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] In communications, the lower limit of latency is determined by the medium being used to transfer information.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] In reliable two-way communication systems, latency limits the maximum rate at which information can be transmitted, as there is often a limit on the amount of information that is in-flight at any given moment.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Perceptible latency has a strong effect on user satisfaction and usability in the field of human–machine interaction.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Online games are sensitive to latency (lag), since fast response times to new events occurring during a game session are rewarded while slow response times may carry penalties.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Due to a delay in transmission of game events, a player with a high-latency internet connection may show slow responses in spite of appropriate reaction time.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] This gives players with low-latency connections a technical advantage.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Trading using computers has developed to the point where millisecond improvements in network speeds offer a competitive advantage for financial institutions.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] However, in a non-trivial network, a typical packet will be forwarded over multiple links and gateways, each of which will not begin to forward the packet until it has been completely received.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] In such a network, the minimal latency is the sum of the transmission delay of each link, plus the forwarding latency of each gateway.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] In practice, minimal latency also includes queuing and processing delays.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Queuing delay occurs when a gateway receives multiple packets from different sources heading toward the same destination.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Since typically only one packet can be transmitted at a time, some of the packets must queue for transmission, incurring additional delay.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Processing delays are incurred while a gateway determines what to do with a newly received packet.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Bufferbloat can also cause increased latency that is an order of magnitude or more.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] The combination of propagation, serialization, queuing, and processing delays often produces a complex and variable network latency profile.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Latency limits total throughput in reliable two-way communication systems as described by the bandwidth-delay product.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Latency in optical fiber is largely a function of the speed of light.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] This would equate to a latency of 3.33 μs for every kilometer of path length.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] The index of refraction of most fiber optic cables is about 1.5, meaning that light travels about 1.5 times as fast in a vacuum as it does in the cable.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] This works out to about 5.0 μs of latency for every kilometer.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] In shorter metro networks, higher latency can be experienced due to extra distance in building risers and cross-connects.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] To calculate the latency of a connection, one has to know the distance traveled by the fiber, which is rarely a straight line, since it has to traverse geographic contours and obstacles, such as roads and railway tracks, as well as other rights-of-way.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Due to imperfections in the fiber, light degrades as it is transmitted through it.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] For distances of greater than 100 kilometers, amplifiers or regenerators are deployed.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Latency introduced by these components needs to be taken into account.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Low Earth orbit is sometimes used to cut this delay, at the expense of more complicated satellite tracking on the ground and requiring more satellites in the satellite constellation to ensure continuous coverage.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Audio latency is the delay between when an audio signal enters and when it emerges from a system.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Potential contributors to latency in an audio system include analog-to-digital conversion, buffering, digital signal processing, transmission time, digital-to-analog conversion and the speed of sound in air.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Video latency refers to the degree of delay between the time a transfer of a video stream is requested and the actual time that transfer begins.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Networks that exhibit relatively small delays are known as low-latency networks, while their counterparts are known as high-latency networks.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Any individual workflow within a system of workflows can be subject to some type of operational latency.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] It may even be the case that an individual system may have more than one type of latency, depending on the type of participant or goal-seeking behavior.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] This is best illustrated by the following two examples involving air travel.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] From the point of view of a passenger, latency can be described as follows.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Suppose John Doe flies from London to New York.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] The latency of his trip is the time it takes him to go from his house in England to the hotel he is staying at in New York.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] This is independent of the throughput of the London-New York air link, whether there were 100 passengers a day making the trip or 10000, the latency of the trip would remain the same.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] From the point of view of flight operations personnel, latency can be entirely different.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Consider the staff at the London and New York airports.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Only a limited number of planes are able to make the transatlantic journey, so when one lands, they must prepare it for the return trip as quickly as possible.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] However, cleaning, refueling and loading the cargo can be done at the same time.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Passengers can only be loaded after cleaning is complete.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] The people involved in the turnaround are interested only in the time it takes for their individual tasks.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] When all of the tasks are done at the same time, however, it is possible to reduce the latency to the length of the longest task.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] If some steps have prerequisites, it becomes more difficult to perform all steps in parallel.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] In the example above, the requirement to clean the plane before loading passengers results in a minimum latency longer than any single task.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Any mechanical process encounters limitations modeled by Newtonian physics.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] The behavior of disk drives provides an example of mechanical latency.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Here, it is the time seek time for the actuator arm to be positioned above the appropriate track and then rotational latency for the data encoded on a platter to rotate from its current position to a position under the disk read-and-write head.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Computers run instructions in the context of a process.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] In the context of computer multitasking, the execution of the process can be postponed if other processes are also executing.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] In addition, the operating system can schedule when to perform the action that the process is commanding.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] For example, suppose a process commands that a computer card's voltage output be set high-low-high-low and so on at a rate of 1000 Hz.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] The operating system schedules the process for each transition (high-low or low-high) based on a hardware clock, such as the High Precision Event Timer.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] The latency is the delay between the events generated by the hardware clock and the actual transitions of voltage from high to low or low to high.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Many desktop operating systems have performance limitations that create additional latency.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] The problem may be mitigated with real-time extensions and patches such as PREEMPT RT.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] On embedded systems, the real-time execution of instructions is often supported by a real-time operating system.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Note that in software systems, benchmarking against *average* and *median* latency can be misleading because a few outliers can distort them.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Instead, software architects and software developers should use "99th percentile".
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] In simulation applications, latency refers to the time delay, often measured in milliseconds, between initial input and output clearly discernible to the simulator trainee or simulator subject.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Latency is sometimes also called *transport delay*.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] Some authorities distinguish between latency and transport delay by using the term *latency* in the sense of the extra time delay of a system over and above the reaction time of the vehicle being simulated, but this requires detailed knowledge of the vehicle dynamics and can be controversial.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] In simulators with both visual and motion systems, it is particularly important that the latency of the motion system not be greater than of the visual system, or symptoms of simulator sickness may result.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] This is because, in the real world, motion cues are those of acceleration and are quickly transmitted to the brain, typically in less than 50 milliseconds; this is followed some milliseconds later by a perception of change in the visual scene.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] The visual scene change is essentially one of change of perspective or displacement of objects, such as the horizon, which takes some time to build up to discernible amounts after the initial acceleration that caused the displacement.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/latency-engineering] A simulator should, therefore, reflect the real-world situation by ensuring that the motion latency is equal to or less than that of the visual system and not the other way round.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] Technical standards for MEC are being developed by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute, which has produced a technical white paper about the concept.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] MEC provides a distributed computing environment for application and service hosting.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] It also can store and process content close to cellular subscribers, for faster response time.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] Applications can also be exposed to real-time radio access network (RAN) information.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] The key element is the MEC application server, which is integrated at the RAN element.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] This server provides computing resources, storage capacity, connectivity, and access to RAN information.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] It supports a multitenancy run-time and hosting environment for applications.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] The virtual appliance applications are delivered as packaged operating system virtual machine (VM) images or containers incorporating operating systems and applications.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] The platform also provides a set of middleware applications and infrastructure services.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] Application software can be provided by equipment vendors, service providers, and third parties.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] The MEC application server can be deployed at the macro base station EnodeB that is part of an LTE cellular network, or at the Radio Network Controller (RNC) that is part of a 3G cellular network, and at a multi-technology cell aggregation site.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] The multi-technology cell aggregation site can be located indoors or outdoors.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] By using mobile edge computing technology, a cellular operator can efficiently deploy new services for specific customers or classes of customers.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] The technology also reduces the signal load of the core network and can host applications and services in a less costly way.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] It also collects data about storage, network bandwidth, CPU utilization, etc., for each application or service deployed by a third party.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] Application developers and content providers can take advantage of proximity to cellular subscribers and real-time RAN information.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] MEC has been created using open standards and application programming interfaces (APIs), using common programming models, relevant tool chains, and software development kits to encourage and expedite the development of new applications for the new MEC environment.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] Since MEC architecture has only recently been proposed, there are as yet very few applications that have adopted this architecture.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] However, many case studies have been proposed in recent articles.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] Some applications that incorporate MEC were made available in 2015.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] For example, active device location tracking allows operators to track active terminal equipment, independent of Global Positioning System devices.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] This is based on third-party geolocation algorithms within an application hosted on the MEC application server.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] Another use is distributed content and Domain Name System (DNS) caching, which reduces server load and speeds up delivery of data to customers.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] The first commercial product available at a bigger scale is AWS Wavelength.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] Customers are able to run their applications on AWS services at the edge of a 4G/5G network of a specific telco.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] Technical standards for MEC are being developed by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI), which created a new Industry Specification Group in 2014 for this purpose.
[src:cloud-edge-computing/mobile-edge-computing] The participating companies are: Allot Communications Systems Ltd, ASTRI, AT&T, B-Com, Cadzow Communications Consulting, Ceragon Networks, Cisco Systems Belgium, ETRI, Eurecom, Fujitsu Laboratories of Europe, Hewlett-Packard France, Huawei TechnologiesFrance, Huawei Technologies(UK) Co.
